## 3. Enforcing TLS Pinning and Certificate Transparency

Network attacks like MITM (Man-in-the-Middle) can intercept or alter your app’s API calls. TLS pinning ensures only your server’s certificate is accepted.

### Implementing Certificate Pinning with OkHttp

Install `okhttp` and `okhttp-tls`:

```gradle
implementation "com.squareup.okhttp3:okhttp:4.12.0"
implementation "com.squareup.okhttp3:okhttp-tls:4.12.0"
```

```kotlin
fun getPinnedClient(context: Context): OkHttpClient {
    val certificatePinner = CertificatePinner.Builder()
        .add(
            "yourdomain.com",
            "sha256/AbCdEf123456...", // Public key hash
            "sha256/XyZaBc67890..."  // Backup key hash
        )
        .build()

    return OkHttpClient.Builder()
        .certificatePinner(certificatePinner)
        .sslSocketFactory(
            getSSLSocketFactory(context),
            getTrustManager() as X509TrustManager
        )
        .build()
}

private fun getSSLSocketFactory(context: Context): SSLSocketFactory {
    val trustManager = getTrustManager()
    val sslContext = SSLContext.getInstance("TLS")
    sslContext.init(null, arrayOf(trustManager), null)
    return sslContext.socketFactory
}

private fun getTrustManager(): X509TrustManager {
    val trustManagerFactory = TrustManagerFactory.getInstance(
        TrustManagerFactory.getDefaultAlgorithm()
    )
    trustManagerFactory.init(null as KeyStore?)
    return trustManagerFactory.trustManagers.first { it is X509TrustManager } as X509TrustManager
}
```

> 🔐 Real-World Tip: Use tools like [SSL Labs](https://www.ssllabs.com) to generate pin hashes. Rotate pins periodically and include backup keys to avoid downtime during certificate renewals.

### Certificate Transparency

While pinning secures against specific certs, Certificate Transparency (CT) ensures no rogue certificates are issued. Use tools like [Facebook’s Conduit](https://github.com/facebook/conduit) or rely on modern Android’s default CT enforcement.

> Android 7.0+ blocks apps from trusting user-added CAs by default (enforces system CA store). This prevents MITM via custom proxies like Charles or Fiddler unless explicitly allowed.

